node.text:
Spoken Poetry today.
I've been deliberating on this for a while now but could never find the courage or comfort to put it up. 
But here goes, let me know how you like it, 
Honest feedbacks much appreciated 🤍
.
.
🔸
There's a field I walk on barefoot, unafraid of the dirt that clings to my skin because this is soil where feelings come to die, unsoiled, unsullied. 

I'm a mortician for the unclaimed performing final rites as I scrub away the blood from wounds unhealed and wrap it neatly beneath white sheets. There's a purity in death that washes away the taint of life, so I lay to rest that which I hope will remain unperturbed;
You who never found peace in your existence, 
May you rest easy in extinction. 

I dig up pits in the ground to resemble the pits in my stomach from which I gave birth to those I now bury beneath my feet before they ever learned to walk;
You who never learnt to take your first breath out of the womb,
May you never need another as you lay in your tomb. 

I say a prayer as I build a graveyard without headstones, without labels, without names;
You who was never recognised in life,
May you learn that remembrance serves you no purpose in death. 

There are poems I write, 
unafraid of the ink that stains my skin because this is ink where feelings come to drown;
I recite them like a prayer, 
You ask me why I write, 
I tell you ,
"To bury dead parts of me so that I may live just right.
🔸 
. 
.
@silverleafpoetry @bleedingsoulpoetry @streetwritersofficial 
@unerasepoetry 
@poemsindia 
@evepoetrygroup

node.text:
[Scroll/Swipe to Read] :
🔸
Somewhere in this City - 

Somewhere in this city, a mother tended to her crying child with a scraped knee from a tussle with an inconsiderate stretch of rough tar; 
The Mother beat the ground as punishment,
And kissed his leg for the pain. 
The child learned two things that day -
One, the world is tough, but his mother is tougher.
And two, the world was better off soft, like his mother's kiss. 

Somewhere in this city, a heartbroken lover salts her dinner with her tears, over a heartless man who left her. 
One glass of wine becomes two, 
two glasses become four,
Till she falls asleep in her own embrace under the warmth she bought in a bottle. 
She wakes to the gentle kiss of a filtered sun that flits through her curtains and she thinks of two things - 
One, life is cruel but not as cruel as love. 
And two, life would be better if love was gentle, like the morning sun. 

Somewhere in this city, a man in blue shorts tends to stray pups lying limp on the sidewalk, having barely survived the frigid night. 
A woman steps out of her building to throw away the previous nights' tear crusted dinner gone cold,
Only to be asked by the man if she'd let him have it, to feed the dogs. 
She hands him the food and asks if she could join, 
He smiles as bright as the sun before he says he'd love that,
There's a kindness in his voice that's hard to come by.
She asks him why he cares as much for strays on a random street, 
He scratches an old scar on his knee before he says "My mother taught me two things as a child - that the world is tough and I need to be tougher, but that the world is better off soft if I could help it."
And she tells him how she woke up thinking life was cruel, 
But right now, it seems a lot kinder. 

Somewhere in this city, 
The morning sun came with the promise of a new day with warm breaths,
The world is softer, 
Love is a little more gentle, 
And life was a whole lot better. 
.
.
.
#ofwheelsandwords

[Swipe to Read] : 
🔸
Posting the second version based off the same prompts and this time it's a love poem. 
Also leaving more relevant facts here - 

1. About three in four of India’s districts are hotspots of extreme climate events such as cyclones, floods, drought, heat and cold waves, according to a study by the Council on Energy, Environment and Water (CEEW), a research agency.

2. In 2019, India witnessed 16 extreme flood events, which affected 151 districts. The study found that over 9.7 crore (97 million) people are currently exposed to extreme floods in India. Six of India’s eight most flood-prone districts in the last decade — Barpeta, Darrang, Dhemaji, Goalpara, Golaghat, Sivasagar — are in Assam. The last 50 years also recorded a 12-fold surge in the number of associated cyclonic events such as extreme rainfall, floods, and thunderstorms. 

3. The frequency, intensity, and unpredictability of these extreme events have risen in recent decades – while India witnessed 250 extreme climate events in 35 years between 1970 and 2005, it recorded 310 such weather events in only 15 years since then, the study has pointed out. The study also found a shift in the pattern of extreme climate events such as flood-prone areas becoming drought-prone and vice-versa in over 40% of districts. 

*Refer to previous take for the rest. 
Hope you like it :) 🌻
.
.
#ofwheelsandwords

Image may contain: text that says 'The world in my hands /On Unrequited Love: The world is breaking in the middle of my palms which is to say I've been holding my heart out for you but so far all that's left of us are mistakes turned fault lines running on these red walls that still beats to your name. I'd have moved heaven and earth for you but all that's changed are these tectonic plates you've pushed out of place; I've got tremors in my hands from carrying a heart that trembles frantically at the sound of your voice.'.

Photo by Shaaz Ahmed on January 31, 2021. Image may contain: text that says 'The world is moulding itself in my grasp which is to say I've changed and I've changed for you but there's only so far / can go before my heart is no longer a heart and can barely recognise myself. Gaia theory says that Earth is a living breathing organism that adapts to help life thrive. But a mere 0.6°C rise in temperature in the last 100 years results in catastrophic climate, And / wonder how much longer have before adapting to you means my own extinction.'.

Photo by Shaaz Ahmed on January 31, 2021. Image may contain: text that says 'The world is bleeding through my fingers which is to say/ would dedicate my entire life to you but there's only so much / can bleed before I'm bled dry. There's a warm westerly wind which arises from the Pacific called the Chinook that is so dry, it vapourises snow on contact. / can't help but think that this love I carry as deep as the ocean has been left out to dry, that I'm afraid the next person I touch will at best, turn to dust.'.

Photo by Shaaz Ahmed on January 31, 2021. Image may contain: text that says 'You see, I'm a man of science but all the research do hardly explains this pit that forms in my stomach like the centre of a storm waiting to arrive only to pull me apart. The last 50 years recorded a 12 fold surge in associated cyclone events like thunderstorms, extreme rainfall and floods. Now, three out of four districts in india are hotspots of extreme weather climate. And don't know how to tell you that/ could move to the safest one and you'd still hit me like a fucking hurricane.'.
Photo by Shaaz Ahmed on January 31, 2021. Image may contain: text that says '// The world is in my hands, You held them as you liked, And now it's breaking. -s.a'.

node.text:
[Swipe/Scroll to Read] 
🔸 
Prompt by @silverleafpoetry : Write a poem inspired by "The pain I don't say out loud builds a home inside me."
#silverleafcontest 
🔸
Of Homes With Closed Doors : 

I was a little boy taught not to lie because dishonesty isn't tolerated in a household built on unspoken truths and whitewashed pretences.
My father like his father before him, has been taught that strength lies in silent sufferings and muted miseries because it is unbecoming of a man to raise his voice if not to fight. 

I was a little boy mistaken for a girl 
when I was 9, because I cried that day and 
mother said, "Hush little child, how are you
to become a man if you can't hold back tears, have you ever seen your father cry? 
You have much to learn." 
So I swallowed my tears to water the pain
That I buried beneath my throat
And watched it take root. 

I am a man now, six and twenty years old, 
There's a wilting garden that lays
beneath my ribs, and everytime I'm asked how I feel, I pick dead flowers from between my teeth and weave a wreath I hang at the
door to my chest. 

I had much to learn and so I did, 
on blackboards with white chalks
I wrote white lies to paint bright smiles; 
And on white sheets with black ink
I wrote dark secrets to hide sullen cries. 

I was a little boy taught to build walls 
and no windows, so I burnt chalks to make
lime, and cement my lies within my bones.
"Be a fortress, stand tall", said my father;
But father, a fortress that isn't a home first, is just a prison. 

Now I'm a man fully grown with four limbs for four walls, no windows and a closed door, watering dead plants in the hope that one day, 
sunlight will find me through the door I haven't learnt to open yet. 
.
.
#ofwheelsandwords

node.text:
[Swipe To Read] 
🔸
I wrote another fact based poem thanks to @_de_wang_ , 
And the prompt - "Start a poem with The world is breaking in the middle of my palms." by @_selcouthsouls . 

Originally wrote yet another love poem which was pointed out and suggested that I try something different so I ended up with this.
 [ I will put that up as well in due time, let me know in the comments if I should. ] 
As I write this I'm aware how little and how much more I need to do to make our lives more sustainable. 

Leaving the relevant facts here for more clarity - 

1. Earth is a perfect planet for life but, according to Gaia theory, this is no coincidence. From the moment life first appeared on Earth it has worked hard to make Earth a more comfortable place to live. Gaia theory suggests that the Earth and its natural cycles can be thought of like a living organism. When one natural cycle starts to go out of kilter other cycles work to bring it back, continually optimising the conditions for life on Earth. 
Named after the Greek Earth goddess, Gaia, the theory was developed in the 1960s by scientist Dr James Lovelock.

2. In the western U.S., there's a wind called the Chinook, or "snow eater," that vaporizes snow before it even has a chance to melt.
Chinook winds are westerlies from the Pacific whose moisture gets wrung out as it passes over the Rocky Mountains. Once these winds come down onto the high plains, the air is so dry that when it hits a snowpack, the frozen water evaporates, going directly from the ice to vapor and bypassing the liquid phase entirely.

3. The hottest decade on record is coming to a close, with the last five years being the hottest since 1880. 2020 is just two-hundredths of a degree cooler than 2016, the hottest year ever recorded. The Earth is nearly 2 degrees Fahrenheit warmer now than it was in the 20th century, and greenhouse gas concentrations in the atmosphere are still rising.

4.The last 50 years also recorded a 12-fold surge in the number of associated cyclonic events such as extreme rainfall, floods, and thunderstorms. 
.
.
#ofwheelsandwords

node.text:
[Swipe / Scroll to Read] - 
.
.
@_selcouthsouls asked two things - 
1. Write a poem that incorporates the recipe of my favourite dish so here we are.
2. Start a poem with "The god is hungry and he decides to" 
🔸
The god is hungry and he decides to make a dish so complex, I tell you it's a wonder that it held together even with my name on it. 

When you ask me what makes me a writer, I tell you there are three parts to me;

I am one part sauce put together intricately when ground meat meets browned onions and garlic in a pot before it is drowned in crushed tomatoes, seasoned with salt, oregano, parsley and pepper then brought to a simmer;
Which is to say I am flesh tenderised with burnt tears and red blood that flows within these veins which boils when provoked to spill poetry on paper seasoned with just enough character to provide some depth to the person I am, lest I remain too shallow. 

I am one part cheese - ricotta, mozzarella and parmesan blended together to bring out the right flavour that sits well with the sauce; 
Which is to say I am warm emotions that coat my body to feel love in all forms before I have felt and I've hurt enough to learn the right amount of love it takes to make me whole. 

I am one part solid pasta cut in sheets, boiled with salt and olive oil to keep everything together in shape without making a mess; 
Which is to say I am soft skin stretched over to hold myself together, when I'm falling apart, to give me strength and embody everything I am on the inside. 

When you ask me why I am the way I am, 
I tell you that these parts of me have been taken and set in layer upon layer and thrown into an oven till I'm cooked through and through and all anyone can ever hope to do is pick away pieces of myself till they reach the very bottom of the plate and hope to god that you don't lose your appetite halfway through. 

You see, god was hungry but so were his children, 
So he left me here on his kitchen table to feed them, 
All he does is keep adding layers and call it growth,
And all I do is give and give and give,
Till I am nothing but crumbs left on a plate. 

- Shaaz, a human lasagne. 
.
.
#ofwheelsandwords

[Swipe To Read] - 

Random science and history from @_de_wang_ put me in a mood.
So to give more clarity, I'll leave them here - 

1. Article II of the Outer Space Treaty says that you cannot appropriate the Moon for national sovereignty,” Bridenstine, Administrator of NASA said “We fully agree with that and embrace it. We also believe that, just like in the ocean, you can extract resources from the ocean. But that doesn’t mean you own the ocean. You should be able to extract resources from the Moon. Own the resources but not own the Moon.”

2. Kessler effect - a theoretical scenario in which the density of low Earth orbit objects increases due to space pollution and becomes high enough that collisions between objects could cause a cascading effect, increasing the risk of further collisions. This would ultimately foreclose use of low earth orbital resources. If true, this would mean that even objects heading to geostationary orbit or farther into space (e.g., to the moon and Mars), would face increasing dangers as they travel through lower orbits.

3. History of the german Wonder Weapon V-2 and its creator, Werner Von Braun.

node.text:
[Scroll/Swipe To Read] :

There are nights I find myself sleeping next to you, but I've never felt further apart.
There's a disconnect in this sense of comfort that I cannot seem to touch, yet invariably drown in. 
Like a candle behind a veil of glass - I am freezing looking at what is undeniably all the warmth I need.
Like a candle I hold in my hands - dripping molten wax onto my fingers, leaving blisters before the fire swallows me whole. 
That is to say we are neither here nor there, 
And I wish I was the veil of glass instead. 
You call me your lucky star;
I tell you, you're my sun and moon, but reality reminds me that I am the astronaut ceaselessly drifting in endless space, 
Lagrange points hold me between the warmth that is your body and the cold of your touch. 

There's a war story about a man, Hideki Tojo who tried to resist arrest by shooting himself in the chest, but missed and ended up with a bullet in his stomach, 
And I can't help but think about how I was certain you held my heart only to realise that your name now leaves a sinking feeling in my gut. 

In prison during trial, he was given new dentures by an American dentist on which was drilled a message, "Remember Pearl Harbor", as a reminder for his crimes.
And I think of how you held and kissed me fiercely as you carved your name with your tongue on the inside of my cheeks.
It still burns from time to time,
And I am left wondering when love started to feel like a prison and your name my atonement. 

He survived, and so did I. 
We're survivors who apologize for surviving,
Who apologize for not dying fast enough, 
We're survivors whose names will go down in history,
With our sins our greatest legacy. 

Hideki Tojo was sentenced to death on November 12, 1948 and hanged 41 days later - 41 days knowing his life was hanging by a thread,
Till it snapped, same as his neck. 
I wonder how many days it's been since I've started feeling the same way everytime you put your arms around me. 

(Contd. In Comments) 
.
.
#ofwheelsandwords

node.text:
[Swipe To Read] 
Conversations in my head (3/3). 
.
.
I've been dwelling on the past a lot lately, it's not something I usually do but I feel like a part of me is trying to remember something important that I've been forgetting. 
What a funny fickle thing, memory. 
I look for reasons in the past to understand why I am the way I am, 
All while telling myself that it changes nothing, 
What I will be tomorrow is not dictated by my past, 
It is my choice as I stand right now. 
I read a quote the other day that said, "You are free to choose, but you are not free from the consequences of your choice." 
And it's been stuck in my head, how do I choose change now when the consequences of my choices in the past are still not done catching up with me? 
What a paradoxical living,
What a blessing to be able to think. 
.
.
.
#ofwheelsandwords

node.text:
[Swipe To Read] :
Conversations in my Head (2/3).
.
.
Gentle reminder for those of you that need it today, there will always come a better day. 

I've been trying to write more from a place of hope. 
Mostly because I feel like on most days I tend to focus on all the things that went wrong, 
trying to give it some sense of value and turn it into something that spells out growth for me, because if I didn't grow from it, have I really made the best of it? 
But maybe, it is what it is, and being so focused on it and this desperate attempt to turn pain and sorrow into art and productivity, into something positive leaves me neglecting the actual positives in my life.
So leaving this here for anyone that needs to hear it, 
The sun will rise again. 
.
.
.

node.text:
Himawari [Swipe/Scroll to read.] : 

1. There's a girl in yellow who sowed sunflower seeds into my hands and whispered to me that I am all things sunshine. 

2. There are crescent scars on my palms from where the seeds are buried to remind me that I am but the fertile moon that thrives on sunlight much like the flowers that now bloom beneath my skin. 

3. She tells me I am both. And for the days I choose to be the moon, I will have her sun. 

4. Roots take hold in the spaces between my fingers to hold my hand the same way she held mine and I feel a little less alone. 

5. I have yellow petals for fingernails now, they grow softer, lighter; 
And the way I hold myself turns more gentle with each passing day. 

6. Days bleed into nightfall and seasons pass as my hands now wilt but she takes them in hers anyway and tells me they're as soft as ever. 

7. I am now a shower of dried petals that fall unto myself. She picks them up and hides them between the favourite pages of her book. 

8. She tells me, even withered I am every season she wishes to weather. 

9. I push the seeds left scattered along my skin under the dermis, and recite her name like a prayer. 

10. I tell her I am the moon today and she holds me close. She is warm like the sun. 

11. Flowers now sprout from my neck and my shoulders. They hold her as I bloom in her embrace. 

12. My lips turn into leaves that now rustle poetry under her breath, you will find the sun in my eyes, the moon under my tongue and her name in the veins of my poem. 

13. There's a sunflower girl who stands in the middle of a sunflower field.
She smiles and I tell her she is all things sunshine. 

//I wilt only to bloom again, 
I fall for her only to get up and stay. 
.
.
Ending 2020 with this lovely @_kirabiyakana_ series. 
.
.

node.text:
Bhargavi/Parvati/Daughter of the Mountain.
[Swipe/Scroll to Read] 
➡️
I sit beneath the shade cast by the thrones of goddesses who watch intently as their value is weighed in gold by a harassment of bickering men who call themselves top brass, and yet if you asked me I'd tell you they're insignificant flies that have alloyed together to spread rot and disease sold neatly in a package, as gospel to be followed. 

These are merchants of massacre that claim to speak the verses of heaven as they rape the dieties they should have worshipped, 
These are holy men who wrap themselves in the word of God as they strip away the dignity of their mother who gave birth to them as they bathe in the sins of flesh. 

These are righteous men who speak of lineage and heredity and blood, but blood is only pure so long as they run within veins and not flow between legs. 
These are honourable men who smear the head of a woman in vermilion to reflect the red in his eyes only to mark her skin in black and blue because he put a roof over her head and he misses the night sky with his glass of whiskey. 

These are pious men who pray for sons
By beating the wombs of daughters of other men, 
Who blame their wives for the daughter they now raise,
You see they are greedy men who bury their treasure alive because X marks the spot and they don't ask why the Y in their seed let them down. 

These are visionary men who claim to see the light as they turn a blind eye to the woes of women and teach them to stifle their cries so that they may read their holy scriptures in braille off their broken skin. 

I sit in the wake of a goddess at the feet of mountains of sacrilege,
In the valley of irreverence nestled in the follies of men,
And I write and I write and I write, 
I write because the truth can never be said enough,
I write because the truth is never told enough, 
I write because I hear her heart beat the throes of revolution. 

The daughter of the mountain will rise,
And the first stone shall fall,
The earth will shift beneath their feet before it swallows them whole. 

//Bhargavi, the mountains will crumble.

In frame : @_kirabiyakana_
📸 : @dusht_ravan
.
.
#ofkirabsandwords 
#ofwheelsandwords
